"title": "7907: baptism, practice of",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7907: baptism, practice of",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Baptism is associated with repenting of sin, believing the gospel message and becoming a member of Christ's body.</p>\n<h2>Baptism is ordained by Jesus Christ himself</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt28:19\">MAT 28:19</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:17-Acts9:18\">ACT 9:17–9:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:14-Acts16:15\">ACT 16:14–16:15</a></p>\n<h2>Baptism is linked with repentance</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:38\">ACT 2:38</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb6:1-Heb6:2\">HEB 6:1–6:2</a> <em>The “baptisms” referred to here may imply teaching about Jewish rituals or the baptism offered by John the Baptist.</em></p>\n<h2>Baptism follows the decision to believe</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:41\">ACT 2:41</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:8\">ACT 18:8</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts8:12-Acts8:13\">ACT 8:12–8:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:31-Acts16:33\">ACT 16:31–16:33</a></p>\n<h2>Baptism in the name of God or Jesus Christ</h2>\n<h3>Baptism in or into the name of Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts19:5\">ACT 19:5</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:38\">ACT 2:38</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts8:16\">ACT 8:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts10:48\">ACT 10:48</a></p>\n<h3>Baptism in the name of the Trinity</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt28:18-Matt28:20\">MAT 28:18–28:20</a></p>\n<h2>Baptism was by immersion</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom6:4\">ROM 6:4</a></strong> <em>The word “buried” implies immersion.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts8:38\">ACT 8:38</a></p>\n<h2>Baptism is linked with the gift of the Holy Spirit</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:8\">MRK 1:8</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts1:5\">ACT 1:5</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:4\">ACT 2:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts11:16\">ACT 11:16</a><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor12:13\">1CO 12:13</a></strong> <em>All the Christians at Corinth had been spiritually baptised into Christ and thus united with him.</em></p>\n<h2>Manifestations of the Holy Spirit may follow or precede water baptism</h2>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts8:12-Acts8:17\">ACT 8:12–8:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:17-Acts9:18\">ACT 9:17–9:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts10:44-Acts10:48\">ACT 10:44–10:48</a></p>\n<h2>The person who baptises is of little importance</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor1:14\">1CO 1:14</a></strong> <em>What matters is not who baptises but the Saviour in whose name it is done.</em></p>\n<h2>Baptism ``for the dead''</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:29\">1CO 15:29</a></strong> <em>It is not certain if there was a ceremony of baptism “for the dead” in the NT church, nor whether, if it existed, Paul approved of it.</em></p>\n<h2>Passages which may imply infant baptism</h2>\n<p>The ``households'' (not merely individuals) may well have included children:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:15\">ACT 16:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts16:33\">ACT 16:33</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts18:8\">ACT 18:8</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor1:16\">1CO 1:16</a>; \n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark10:13-Mark10:16\">MRK 10:13–10:16</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor7:14\">1CO 7:14</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Col2:11-Col2:12\">COL 2:11–2:12</a> <em>If baptism is here equated with circumcision, this suggests baptism is the sign of the new covenant.</em></p>\n<h2>Passages apparently negating infant baptism</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:38-Acts2:41\">ACT 2:38–2:41</a> <em>infants cannot repent and believe</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal3:7\">GAL 3:7</a> <em>Under the new covenant it is faith in Jesus Christ, not an outward sign, that makes a person a child of God.</em></p>",
